---
import { Code } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';
import StarlightPage from '@astrojs/starlight/components/StarlightPage.astro';

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const coverUrl = `${baseUrl}/cover.png`;
---

<StarlightPage
  frontmatter={{
    title: 'Octopus',
    description:
      'Centralized AI agent configuration for multi-repo teams — skills, bundles, hooks, roles, continuous learning.',
    template: 'splash',
    hero: {
      tagline:
        'Centralized AI agent configuration for multi-repo teams. Skills, bundles, hooks, roles, and continuous learning — one source of truth across Claude Code, Codex, Copilot, Gemini, and OpenCode.',
      image: {
        html: `<img src="${coverUrl}" alt="Octopus — centralized AI agent configuration" style="max-width: 380px;" />`,
      },
      actions: [
        { text: 'Install', link: '/octopus/get-started/install/', icon: 'rocket', variant: 'primary' },
        { text: 'What is Octopus', link: '/octopus/get-started/what-is-octopus/', icon: 'document', variant: 'secondary' },
        { text: 'GitHub', link: 'https://github.com/leocosta/octopus', icon: 'github', variant: 'minimal' },
      ],
    },
  }}
>
  <section class="not-content">
    <h2>The problem</h2>
    <p>
      Every team that uses an AI coding agent at scale ends up writing the
      same kinds of configuration over and over: the project's coding
      conventions, the team's commit conventions, the security guardrails,
      the on-call playbooks, the post-mortem rituals. That config grows
      tribal: a long <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, a folder of
      <code>.cursor/rules/*</code>, a half-finished
      <code>copilot-instructions.md</code>. Different agents speak
      different dialects of the same idea.
    </p>
    <p>
      Octopus is the configuration layer that sits above all of them.
      One source of truth — bundles, skills, hooks, roles, knowledge —
      that compiles down into the formats each agent expects. Add a new
      agent, change a coding rule, ship a new audit; one edit, all
      surfaces updated.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="not-content">
    <h2>The five primitives</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/octopus/bundles/">Bundles</a></strong> — opinionated
        packages of skills + roles + rules tuned to a team archetype
        (<code>starter</code>, <code>quality</code>, <code>docs</code>,
        <code>backend</code>, <code>growth</code>).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/octopus/skills/">Skills</a></strong> — protocols
        the agent engages by description match or explicit invocation
        (<code>debug</code>, <code>doc-prd</code>, <code>refactor-deepen</code>,
        <code>audit-config</code>, plus 30+ more).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/octopus:get-started/mental-model/">Commands</a></strong>
        — slash-command entry points that pin a specific skill to a typed
        invocation (<code>/octopus:debug</code>,
        <code>/octopus:context-handoff</code>, …).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/octopus/hooks/">Hooks</a></strong> — lifecycle
        scripts that enforce discipline automatically: format on save,
        block destructive git, propose CLAUDE.md updates at session end.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/octopus/roles/">Roles</a></strong> — personas
        the user can delegate to (<code>@architect</code>,
        <code>@backend-developer</code>, <code>@writer</code>, …)
        that scope an agent's behaviour for one task.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="not-content">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <h3>macOS / Linux</h3>
    <Code code="curl -fsSL https://github.com/leocosta/octopus/releases/latest/download/install.sh | bash" lang="bash" />
    <h3>Windows (PowerShell)</h3>
    <Code code="irm https://github.com/leocosta/octopus/releases/latest/download/install.ps1 | iex" lang="powershell" />
    <p>
      Then <code>octopus update</code> inside any repo to generate the
      agent config files. Full walkthrough on the
      <a href="/octopus/get-started/quickstart/">Quick Start</a> page.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="not-content">
    <h2>Featured workflows</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="/octopus/skills/test-tdd/">TDD a new feature</a> — vertical
        tracer-bullet slices, integration-style tests, hard ban on
        horizontal slicing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/octopus/skills/audit-all/">Pre-merge audit on a billing change</a>
         — composes security + money + tenant + cross-stack contract audits
         in parallel.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/octopus/skills/context-handoff/">Hand off a session</a> —
        compact the conversation into a tmp doc with prescriptive
        suggested-next-skills for the successor agent.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</StarlightPage>

<style>
  section.not-content {
    max-width: 64ch;
    margin: 2.5rem auto;
    padding: 0 1rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  section.not-content h2 {
    margin-top: 0;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
  }
  section.not-content h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }
  section.not-content code {
    background: var(--sl-color-gray-6);
    padding: 0.1em 0.3em;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }
</style>
